column13: Fixed unable to parse multipart form-data request for Safari 10.1
column20:
In Safari 10.1, there is no space char before boundary delimiter in the Content-Type header, the following is an example:
Content-Type: multipart/form-data;boundary=----WebKitFormBoundaryfXkrPTBtsGbpd3XV

This patch handled this situation and made multi-part paring works in Safari 10.1.
column21:

This patch handled this situation and made multi-part paring works in Safari 10.1.

Hello, this patch fixes the warning when compiling swoole on Alpine Linux and similar systems with musl libc:
In file included from /build/main/php7.2-swoole/src/swoole-1.9.15/src/core/socket.c:20:0:
/usr/include/sys/poll.h:1:2: warning: #warning redirecting incorrect #include <sys/poll.h> to <poll.h> [-Wcpp]
 #warning redirecting incorrect #include <sys/poll.h> to <poll.h>

POSIX has example of poll.h and I think it should work ok on most systems these days. Glibc has poll.h also as an option since few years ago.
Thank you for considering merging this or checking it out.

the error information:
PHP Warning:  swoole_event_wait(): Aio Error: Unknown error: 705[705] in Unknown on line 0

Warning: swoole_event_wait(): Aio Error: Unknown error: 705[705] in Unknown on line 0

reason:
The first param of this function is   AF_INET (2) or AF_INET6 (30), but the event->flags == 0 , so the  error happend.

Coroutine::getRuid is based on Coroutine::getUid, but returns a uniq id for each of current requests/receive.
It will always return 1 in callbacks WorkerStart and WorkerStop.

column13: ensure C++ is used for link command
column20:
This may raise very strange issue, especially when building on RHEL / CentOS with gcc from devtoolset (g++ command need to be invoked at link time to produce proper binaries)
Without this change, during the make
libtool: link: cc -shared  -fPIC -DPIC  .libs/swoole.o  ...
With
libtool: link: g++  -fPIC -DPIC -shared -nostdlib /usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-redhat-linux/7/../../../../lib64/crti.o /usr/lib/gcc/x86_64-redhat-linux/7/crtbeginS.o  .libs/swoole.o ...

column21:
Why does not use PSR2 code style directly ? I cannot accept this.

ğŸ‘
Actually, before any changes, these files already don't follow PSR-2. My goal here, was only to make the styles already used, look consistent (e.g., sometimes there was if ( and if(, or tabs + spaces in the same file, etc - these things don't look good), but also, without changing too much (so, only improving aesthetics, and not changing any functionality).
But, I agree with you. Properly following PSR-2 would be better. The files still need work though anyway, I think.
Maybe, we can close this PR (i.e., don't merge these commits), but as an alternative, run these files through a proper PSR-2 validator/fixer (e.g., php-cs-fixer)?
(Also, PSR-2 doesn't address the Codacy/PR complaints. Those would need to still be fixed too, I think).

Hello. The $Id$ keywords were used in Subversion where they can get substituted with last revision number, author, and time. In Git these behave differently and would need to be set in .gitattributes file manually for each file. This patch normalizes this and removes it.
Thanks for considering checking this out or merging it.

column13: Replace obsolete AC_TRY_COMPILE macro with AC_COMPILE_IFELSE
column20:
Hello, Autoconf made several macros obsolete. The AC_TRY_COMPILE macro has been replaced by the AC_COMPILE_IFELSE.
Reference docs: https://www.gnu.org/software/autoconf/manual/autoconf-2.69/html_node/Obsolete-Macros.html
This patch has been tested on Ubuntu and soon will be also done on Alpine which has POSIX shell. Autoconf made this macro obsolete a very long time ago. So, it is pretty much safe to go with the new macro instead.
Thank you for considering checking this out or merging it.

column20:
Certain systems such as Ubuntu Linux distribution with 3rd party PHP repositories build and package PHP sockets extension separately where the php_config.h file doesn't have the HAVE_SOCKETS defined. This constant is used in the ext/sockets/php_sockets.h file and therefore compilation fails with error:
unknown type name â€˜php_socketâ€™; did you mean â€˜php_socket_tâ€™

For these cases, a simple additional definition can be added via the autotools build system.
This patch also checks for the presence of the PHP socket extension header file and provides informational error message in the ./configure --enable-sockets step directly if PHP sockets extension isn't present.
This patch fixes #1454 and #1725

column20:
Main reactor may not exist, when trying to clear signals. e.g. after forking, swoole_process will destroy the main reactor, and then clear signals(in child process). If not handled properly, it will fail silently.


kqueue cannot monitor SIGCHLD, as stated in FreeBSD's man kqueue:

..., except for the SIGCHLD signal, which, if ignored, won't be recorded by the filter.

We may as well use the original solution(signal handler) for it.

column13: Fix building extension from php-src/ext directory
column20:
Hello, this patch addresses #1853
When building extensions directly from the php-src/ext directory, for example to build the extension statically into PHP directly, PHP header files are located in the $abs_srcdir directory.
This patch adds additional check for checking file locations of the socket extension.
Additional macro PHP_ADD_EXTENSION_DEP call is added for more proper initialization order. In case, sockets extension is a dependency, it must be initialized before swoole.
Probably some more additional checks should be made, but I think this should for for many cases so far. In case of issues, let me know.
Thanks.

column20:
Hi, I'm making updates for Open Collective. Either you or a supporter signed this repo up for Open Collective. This pull request adds backers and sponsors from your Open Collective https://opencollective.com/swoole-src â¤ï¸
It adds two badges at the top to show the latest number of backers and sponsors. It also adds placeholders so that the avatar/logo of new backers/sponsors can automatically be shown without having to update your README.md. [more info]. See how it looks on this repo.
You can also add a "Donate" button to your website and automatically show your backers and sponsors there with our widgets. Have a look here: https://opencollective.com/widgets
P.S: As with any pull request, feel free to comment or suggest changes. The only thing "required" are the placeholders on the README because we believe it's important to acknowledge the people in your community that are contributing (financially or with code!).
Thank you for your great contribution to the open source community. You are awesome! ğŸ™Œ
And welcome to the open collective community! ğŸ˜Š
Come chat with us in the #opensource channel on https://slack.opencollective.com - great place to ask questions and share best practices with other open source sustainers!

Hello, this patch trims trailing whitespaces across the source code files to not have these as part of the commits and because some editors trim these automatically when editing files.
For easier viewing of the changes done here there is also ?w=1 GitHub URL parameter, which doesn't show whitespace changes...
Thank you.

column13: Sync final newlines in source code
column20:
Hello,
This patch syncs final newlines in source code files:

trims multiple final newlines into one
adds one final newline where it was missing

According to POSIX, a line is a sequence of zero or more non-' ' characters plus a terminating '' character. [1] Files should normally have at least one final newline character.
C89 standard [2] and above [3] mention a final newline:
"A source file that is not empty shall end in a new-line character, which shall not be immediately preceded by a backslash character."
Newline characters:

LF (\n) (*nix and Mac, default)
CRLF (\r\n) (Windows)
CR (\r) (old Mac, obsolete)

Although it is not mandatory for all files to have this issue fixed, a more consistent and homogeneous approach brings less of commit differences issues and a better development experience in certain text
editors and IDEs.
[1] http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1_chap03.html#tag_03_206
[2] https://port70.net/~nsz/c/c89/c89-draft.html#2.1.1.2
[3] https://port70.net/~nsz/c/c99/n1256.html#5.1.1.2
Thank you.

column20: When a MySql connection object is pulled from a connection pool, there is currently no "cheap" way to check if the connection is really still there before it is injected to the application side. Being able to check SW_MYSQL_STATE_CLOSED first is very efficient and the infrastructure for this is already in place in current code.

column21:
Thank you for the feedback. Yes, the errors should be catched and handled accordingly. That's not what I had in mind and Iâ€™m sorry for not explaining my intentions. In a typical async environment with shared resources, the state can also change for other reasons than errors and closed connection is just one example.
When we have some sleeping connections in our \Swoole\Coroutine\Channel pool and intentionally restart MySql server, all the \Swoole\Coroutine\Mysql objects are returned from pool with state SW_MYSQL_STATE_CLOSED. This data is already in-memory, but not accessible to php side as we have no method for reading it. Since we just restarted the MySql service and we know itâ€™s working, the application could just gracefully replace these closed connections as they are pulled from the pool with new ones without restarting the application or running expensive statements/queries.
Being able to check the state (not just CLOSED, but also QUERY and READ_*) in an async environment with shared connections can be very useful for many things and the getState() method was already implemented in the regular \Swoole\Mysql client module. I think it is a good idea to implement it to \Swoole\Coroutine\Mysql too for compatibility reasons.
Anyway, big thanks for the hard work on this technology, I truly believe Swoole is the best thing to happen to PHP in many years :)

column21:
Well, you canâ€™t really trust this type of â€œisConnectedâ€ method for MySql without actually performing some kind of I/O and thatâ€™s not â€œcheapâ€. I do not recommend that. But, if the state is already closed, you can be pretty sure it is actually closed.
The power of Swoole opens up new possibilities for PHP in situations where it has traditionally not been implemented. I donâ€™t want to sound like smart ass, but letâ€™s say we have an application with heavy load which uses maximum amount of SQL connections during business hours. At night, the DBA have patched a vulnerability in MySql server software and performs a quick restart. All connections in our connection pool on the application side are now in state CLOSED. Since DBA does not own the application, he canâ€™t restart it to reset them. But, itâ€™s OK because our developer already predicted something like this would happen and implemented a simple auto-recovery for replacing closed connections as they are popped out from our Channel. This kind of check does not require any expensive I/O as it would just check the value already in Swoole memory and takes only few lines of code to implement.

column20:
SplQueue is operated using enqueue() and dequeue() not with push() and pop() which is for Stack.
SplQueue is a FIFO, but use of push/pop turns it into Stack which is LIFO, this has caused numerous disconnections that resulted into a swoole server crash.
By fixing this, disconnection from database server does not cause server crash anymore.
Ref.
SplQueue dequeue
SplQueue enqueue

column21:
enqueue && dequeue is as same as push && shift, but this is not the reason for the disconnection,  don't mislead others.
Using pop is indeed a mistake, but any program cannot depend on the order, every time you take a connection from the connection pool, you must check the status of the connection, even try to reconnect after the request fails. The real network is random and uncertain, the connection will be disconnected at any time, even halfway through your request.

column20:
to avoid a spurious wake-up and  unlikely contention in a case where one thread immediately call swoole_futex_wait after the call to syscall(SYS_futex, atomic, FUTEX_WAIT, 0, NULL, NULL, 0)  return justï¼Œwe should validate the return value of  sw_atomic_cmp_set(atomic,1,0) ,  and following is the description of futex mannual:
Note that a wake-up can also be caused by common futex usage patterns in unrelated code that happened to have previously used the futex word's memory location (e.g., typical futex-based implementations of Pthreads mutexes  can  cause  this  under  some  conditions). Therefore,  callers  should  always conservatively assume that a return value of 0 can mean a spurious wake-up, and use the futex word's value (i.e., the  user-space synchronization scheme) to decide whether to continue to block or not.
thanks !

column20:
When sending larger content in $response->end() you will notice that the server performance drops significantly due to high cpu usage. This is observed even though there are almost no cpu intensive computations in the code, this indicates that direct memory access (DMA) is not being taken advantage by the server, resulting to massive degradation in performance.
By enabling zero copy, the cpu will not parse information byte by byte, thus, increasing the performance of the server.
This is still experimental as there should be an implementation for zero copy recv, error handlers and updates for other send/recv functions. Moreover, zero copy send/recv was just recently been available in Linux 4.18 and up.
Some details can be read here https://lwn.net/Articles/726917/ & https://lwn.net/Articles/752188/

also see #2181

Nginx cache purge

Squid cache purge

Having Swoole support would allow it to mimic or proxy the above HTTP servers.

column21:
@twose
Yes, you're right the file uploads format changes for array form fields.
My arguments for accepting the changes:

File uploads format is the same for flat form fields; it has changed only for arrays
All existing file upload tests pass unmodified because they tested flat file uploads only
File uploads format has never been documented, neither for flat nor array form fields
Relying on undocumented functionality comes with backward-compatibility risks
According to you and @matyhtf, array file uploads weren't supported (at least intentionally)

column20:
The POSIX function bzero() is deprecated in IEEE Std 1003.1-2001 and removed in IEEE Std 1003.1-2008.
Although most platforms reserve it for compatibility, it is not guarenteed to exist, even in <strings.h>.
It is recommented that we replace that call with memset() instead, which is a standard ISO C function:
#define sw_bzero(s, n)         memset(s, '\0', n)

column13: Fix headers_sent() with output buffering in coroutines
column20:
Test output buffering ob_*() functions
Assert invariance of headers_sent() state
column21:
@twose
Let me try to to elaborate on the use case in more details.
You're right that the function headers_sent() is generally irrelevant to the Swoole environment. Applications written specifically for Swoole would use \Swoole\Http\Response instead (that doesn't have an equivalent method, but that's okay).
The important thing about headers_sent() is that it affects the built-in session functions. You're right that applications written specifically for Swoole should use a different coroutine-aware mechanism for sessions, such as swoft-cloud/swoft-session or itxiao6/session. However, not all applications are written from scratch with considerations of the Swoole environment specifics. They may rely on the existing libraries/frameworks in the PHP ecosystem not designed with the Swoole compatibility in mind.
Some projects may attempt to retrofit an existing FastCGI/PHP-FPM application for compatibility with Swoole to achieve performance improvements by reusing bootstrapped application state in memory between requests. We have adopted magento/magento2 to run on Swoole to achieve ~35/45% speed up for frontend and Web API requests respectively. We do disable the coroutines and successfully use the PHP sessions. They work just fine and allow for such projects to exist.
The problem is that there's an inconsistency in the headers_sent flag behavior in combination with the output buffering. Everything works as expected when the coroutines are disabled: capturing the output via the ob_*() functions maintains the headers_sent = 0. However, the same exact code works differently with coroutines: the first request has headers_sent = 0 but all subsequent ones have headers_sent = 1. There's no logical reason for such difference in the flag behavior. That's why I'm proposing a simple fix for coroutines.
PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE do not disable the session module as that would be a show stopper for the "classical" applications, such as Magento 2, from ever running on Swoole. If anything, it's better to just decline this PR and keep the sessions working as they are today w/o coroutines. I still think the simple headers_sent fix would be appropriate.
Please let me know if you have further questions. Open to discuss further offline.

column13: Add enable hook can only be run in CLI mode
column20:
When use hook in non-PHP CLI mode, some methods will not be found, such as
Swoole\Runtime::enableCoroutine(): function 'swoole_exec' is not callable
So we should disable it to make sure we get right error message.

column20:
gcc __sync_xxx implements at some architecture needs an aligned address to be passed in, but an allocated address may not be aligned, this patch will align it at atomic implement
this should fix #4263, but not tested at m1 chips (only at arm64 linux).

Allow applications to control max concurrent requests on each worker (Linux) process

Allow Laravel Octane to use coroutines at the request level to reduce the latency

column21:
solves swoole/ext-postgresql#69 also,
by 
  
    
      swoole-src/config.m4
    
    
        Lines 410 to 478
      in
      968a04d
    
  
  
    

        
          
               if test "$PHP_SWOOLE_PGSQL" != "no"; then 
        

        
          
                   dnl TODO macros below can be reused to find curl things 
        

        
          
                   dnl prepare pkg-config 
        

        
          
                   if test -z "$PKG_CONFIG"; then 
        

        
          
                       AC_PATH_PROG(PKG_CONFIG, pkg-config, no) 
        

        
          
                   fi 
        

        
          
                   AC_MSG_CHECKING(for libpq) 
        

        
          
                   if test "x${LIBPQ_LIBS+set}" = "xset" || test "x${LIBPQ_CFLAGS+set}" = "xset"; then 
        

        
          
                       AC_MSG_RESULT([using LIBPQ_CFLAGS and LIBPQ_LIBS]) 
        

        
          
                   elif test -x "$PKG_CONFIG" ; then 
        

        
          
                       dnl find pkg using pkg-config cli tool 
        

        
          
                       libpq_pkg_config_path="$PHP_SWOOLE_PGSQL/lib/pkgconfig" 
        

        
          
                       if test "xyes" = "x$PHP_SWOOLE_PGSQL" ; then 
        

        
          
                           libpq_pkg_config_path=/lib/pkgconfig 
        

        
          
                       fi 
        

        
          
                       if test "x" != "x$PKG_CONFIG_PATH"; then 
        

        
          
                           libpq_pkg_config_path="$libpq_pkg_config_path:$PKG_CONFIG_PATH" 
        

        
          
                       fi 
        

        
          
            
        

        
          
                       libpq_version_full=`env PKG_CONFIG_PATH=${libpq_pkg_config_path} $PKG_CONFIG --modversion libpq` 
        

        
          
                       AC_MSG_RESULT(${libpq_version_full}) 
        

        
          
                       LIBPQ_CFLAGS="`env PKG_CONFIG_PATH=${libpq_pkg_config_path} $PKG_CONFIG --cflags libpq`" 
        

        
          
                       LIBPQ_LIBS="`env PKG_CONFIG_PATH=${libpq_pkg_config_path} $PKG_CONFIG --libs libpq`" 
        

        
          
                   fi 
        

        
          
            
        

        
          
                   _libpq_saved_cflags="$CFLAGS" 
        

        
          
                   CFLAGS="$CFLAGS $LIBPQ_CFLAGS" 
        

        
          
                   AC_CHECK_HEADER(libpq-fe.h, [], [ 
        

        
          
                       dnl this is too long, wht so chaos? 
        

        
          
                       cat >&2 <<EOF 
        

        
          
           libpq headers was not found. 
        

        
          
           set LIBPQ_CFLAGS and LIBPQ_LIBS environment or 
        

        
          
           install following package to obtain them: 
        

        
          
               libpq-dev (for debian and its varients) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-devel (for rhel varients) 
        

        
          
               libpq-devel (for newer fedora) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-libs (for arch and its varients) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-dev (for alpine) 
        

        
          
               postgresql (for homebrew) 
        

        
          
           EOF 
        

        
          
                       AC_MSG_ERROR([postgresql support needs libpq headers to build]) 
        

        
          
                   ]) 
        

        
          
                   CFLAGS="$_libpq_saved_cflags" 
        

        
          
            
        

        
          
                   _libpq_saved_libs=$LIBS 
        

        
          
                   LIBS="$LIBS $LIBPQ_LIBS" 
        

        
          
                   AC_CHECK_LIB(pq, PQlibVersion, [ ], [ 
        

        
          
                       cat >&2 <<EOF 
        

        
          
           libpq libraries was not found. 
        

        
          
           set LIBPQ_CFLAGS and LIBPQ_LIBS environment or 
        

        
          
           install following package to obtain them: 
        

        
          
               libpq-dev (for debian and its varients) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-devel (for rhel varients) 
        

        
          
               libpq-devel (for newer fedora) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-libs (for arch and its varients) 
        

        
          
               postgresql-dev (for alpine) 
        

        
          
               postgresql (for homebrew) 
        

        
          
           EOF 
        

        
          
                       AC_MSG_ERROR([postgresql support needs libpq libraries to build]) 
        

        
          
                   ]) 
        

        
          
                   LIBS="$_libpq_saved_libs" 
        

        
          
            
        

        
          
                   dnl FIXME: this should be SWOOLE_CFLAGS="$SWOOLE_CFLAGS $LIBPQ_CFLAGS" 
        

        
          
                   dnl or SWOOLE_PGSQL_CFLAGS="$SWOOLE_CFLAGS $LIBPQ_CFLAGS" and SWOOLE_PGSQL_CFLAGS only applies to ext-src/swoole_postgresql_coro.cc 
        

        
          
                   EXTRA_CFLAGS="$EXTRA_CFLAGS $LIBPQ_CFLAGS" 
        

        
          
                   PHP_EVAL_LIBLINE($LIBPQ_LIBS, SWOOLE_SHARED_LIBADD) 
        

        
          
            
        

        
          
                   AC_DEFINE(SW_USE_PGSQL, 1, [do we enable postgresql coro support]) 
        

        
          
               fi

column13: Fix build failure on systems without clock_gettime
column20:
Building swoole 4.8.7 on OS X 10.11.6 and earlier fails:
src/core/timer.cc:256:1: error: expected unqualified-id
if (gettimeofday(time, nullptr) < 0) {
^
src/core/timer.cc:261:5: error: expected unqualified-id
    return SW_OK;
    ^
src/core/timer.cc:264:1: error: extraneous closing brace ('}')
};  // namespace swoole
^

This PR fixes it.
The #if was mistakenly placed before the function signature rather than after when this code was refactored in d6add5e. As a result, a subsequent clang format misformatted the code in 3aa03bb.
Closes #3896

column13: Fix AC_LANG settings for in-tree build
column20:
This affects AX_CHECK_COMPILE_FLAG in Zend/Zend.m4, will cause bad flags support detection when do an in-tree build.
AX_CHECK_COMPILE_FLAG([-Wno-clobbered], CFLAGS="-Wno-clobbered $CFLAGS", , [-Werror])
should be
{ printf "%s\n" "$as_me:${as_lineno-$LINENO}: checking whether C compiler accepts -Wno-clobbered" >&5
printf %s "checking whether C compiler accepts -Wno-clobbered... " >&6; }
if test ${ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered+y}
then :
  printf %s "(cached) " >&6
else $as_nop

  ax_check_save_flags=$CFLAGS
  CFLAGS="$CFLAGS -Werror -Wno-clobbered"
  cat confdefs.h - <<_ACEOF >conftest.$ac_ext
/* end confdefs.h.  */

int
main (void)
{

  ;
  return 0;
}
_ACEOF
if ac_fn_c_try_compile "$LINENO"
then :
  ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered=yes
else $as_nop
  ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered=no
fi
rm -f core conftest.err conftest.$ac_objext conftest.beam conftest.$ac_ext
  CFLAGS=$ax_check_save_flags
fi
{ printf "%s\n" "$as_me:${as_lineno-$LINENO}: result: $ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" >&5
printf "%s\n" "$ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" >&6; }
if test "x$ax_cv_check_cflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" = xyes
then :
  CFLAGS="-Wno-clobbered $CFLAGS"
else $as_nop
  :
fi
if AC_LANG is not resetted, this will check CXX instead (zend wont use CXXFLAG):
{ printf "%s\n" "$as_me:${as_lineno-$LINENO}: checking whether C++ compiler accepts -Wno-clobbered" >&5
printf %s "checking whether C++ compiler accepts -Wno-clobbered... " >&6; }
if test ${ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered+y}
then :
  printf %s "(cached) " >&6
else $as_nop

  ax_check_save_flags=$CXXFLAGS
  CXXFLAGS="$CXXFLAGS -Werror -Wno-clobbered"
  cat confdefs.h - <<_ACEOF >conftest.$ac_ext
/* end confdefs.h.  */

int
main (void)
{

  ;
  return 0;
}
_ACEOF
if ac_fn_cxx_try_compile "$LINENO"
then :
  ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered=yes
else $as_nop
  ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered=no
fi
rm -f core conftest.err conftest.$ac_objext conftest.beam conftest.$ac_ext
  CXXFLAGS=$ax_check_save_flags
fi
{ printf "%s\n" "$as_me:${as_lineno-$LINENO}: result: $ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" >&5
printf "%s\n" "$ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" >&6; }
if test "x$ax_cv_check_cxxflags__Werror__Wno_clobbered" = xyes
then :
  CFLAGS="-Wno-clobbered $CFLAGS"
else $as_nop
  :
fi
while at centos, ac_fn_cxx_try_compile may broken (CFLAGS is set, but only CXXFLAG is used in compiling test), this may be a libtool/autoconf bug:
configure:99672: checking whether C++ compiler accepts -Wno-clobbered
configure:99692: cc -std=gnu99 -std=gnu99 -c -Wall -Wextra -Wno-strict-aliasing -Wno-unused-parameter -Wno-sign-compare -static-libgcc -I/include -fvisibility=hidden -pthread  -D_REENTRANT conftest.c >&5
configure:99692: $? = 0
configure:99701: result: yes

(note that '-Wno-clobbered' is not in the test command args)
This may cause strange build failure...
